    <section>
        <h3>2.2 Pythagorean theorem</h3>
        <p>
        In any right triangle \(\triangle ABC\), where c is the length of the hypotenuse and a and b are the lengths of the legs,
        </p>

        <div class="container">
        <div class="center">\(a^2 + b^2 = c^2\)</div>
        <div class="right" id="[2.1]">[2.2]</div>
        </div>

        <figure class="centered">
        <img
            src="/images/RightTriangle.svg"
            width="300"
            height="225"
            alt="Right triangle diagram"
        />
        <figcaption>
            <b>Figure 2.1</b> Right triangle with hypotenuse c and legs a and b.
        </figcaption>
        </figure>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h3>2.3 Graphical definitions of sine, cosine and tangent functions</h3>

        <p>
        Let's consider a circunference with radius of length r with centre at the origin <i>O</i> in a
        rectangular coordinate system, and a point P with coordinates (x,y) in the circunference. And let's name &alpha; the angle between the x-axis and the segment OP, as shown in figure below. Then, \(\sin \alpha\) is the ratio y/r, `cos alpha` is the ratio x/r and \(\tan \alpha\) is the ratio y/x.
        </p>

        <figure class="centered">
        <img
            src="/images/Circunference_and_coordinates.svg"
            width="300"
            height="300"
            alt="Diagram of a circle with point P and inscribed right triangle."
        />
        <figcaption>
            <b>Figure 2.2</b> Circunference of radius r with a point P and angle &alpha; with x-axis.
        </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>Then, we define the sine, cosine and tangent functions as:</p>

        <div class="container">
        <div class="center">\(\sin \alpha = y/r\)</div>
        <div class="right" id="[2.2]">[2.2]</div>
        </div>
        <br />

        <div class="container">
        <div class="center">\(\cos \alpha = x/r\)</div>
        <div class="right" id="[2.3]">[2.3]</div>
        </div>
        <br />

        <div class="container">
        <div class="center">\(\tan \alpha = y/x\)</div>
        <div class="right" id="[2.4]">[2.4]</div>
        </div>
        <br />
    </section>

